                                <h2 class="text-center mt-0">TEI Encoding as a Unified Structure for Multilingual
                                    Digital Editions: The LeggoManzoni Case Study at AIUCD 2025</h2>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>June 13, 2025</strong>. At the AIUCD 2025 conference (Associazione per
                                    l'Informatica Umanistica e la Cultura Digitale), the <i>Leggo Manzoni</i> project
                                    was presented through the paper "<i>TEI Encoding as a Unified Structure for
                                        Multilingual Digital Editions: The LeggoManzoni Case Study</i>". The
                                    presentation, delivered by Mariia Levchenko (Università "Alma Mater" di Bologna),
                                    Beatrice Nava (Universität Wien), and Ersilia Russo (Università degli Studi di
                                    Firenze), illustrated the innovative methodological approach developed for creating
                                    multilingual digital editions.
                                </p>
                                 <div class="image-container text-center my-4">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/aiucd_2025.jpg" alt="AIUCD 2025 Conference" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 600px;">
                                </div>

                                <p>
                                    The paper demonstrated how TEI encoding can serve as a unified framework for
                                    managing multiple translations and versions of literary works within a single
                                    digital environment. Using <i>The Betrothed</i> as a case study, the presentation
                                    showcased the technical solutions implemented in the <i>Leggo Manzoni</i> platform
                                    to align and correlate texts across different languages while maintaining scholarly
                                    precision and accessibility for both researchers and students.
                                </p>


