                                <h2 class="text-center mt-0">Visit to the Research Center for Digital Humanities of
                                    Peking University
                                </h2>
                                <p><strong>March 18, 2025</strong>.
                                    The morning of March 18 was dedicated to a visit to the Research Center for Digital
                                    Humanities at Peking University. We were welcomed and guided by Professor <strong>Qi
                                        Su</strong>, one
                                    of the Center’s founders, and the current director, <strong>Jun Wang</strong>, who
                                    showed us the
                                    facilities and introduced us to their research teams.
                                </p>
                                <div class="image-container text-center my-4">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/roberta_1sm.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 600px;">
                                </div>
                                <p>Following the tour, a roundtable discussion was held to share ongoing research
                                    projects and digital practices in the field of Digital Humanities at the University
                                    of Bologna and Peking University. Representing the University of Bologna, Roberta
                                    Priore presented the work of the department’s <a
                                        href="https://site.unibo.it/adlab/it" target="_blank">ADLab</a>, highlighting
                                    the key steps for
                                    proper digitization of archival sources, using the <a
                                        href="https://dl.ficlit.unibo.it/s/lib/page/fondo-giuseppe-raimondi">Giuseppe
                                        Raimondi</a> collection as a
                                    case study. This collection contains a variety of materials, including the author's
                                    handwritten notebooks. Her presentation was followed by an overview of <a
                                        href="https://pdd.ficlit.unibo.it/s/percorsi-di-didattica-digitale/page/home">digital
                                        teaching paths</a>, <a
                                        href="https://exhibits.ficlit.unibo.it/s/browse-ficlit-exhibits/page/home">virtual
                                        exhibitions</a>, and <a
                                        href="https://centri.unibo.it/dharc/en/research/projects-at-dh-arc">digital
                                        editions</a>, with a focus on
                                    the <a
                                        href="https://dharc-org.github.io/progetto-vasto/index.html#Home">VaSto</a>, edition
                                    of Storia fiorentina by Benedetto Varchi.
                                </p>

                                <p>The conversation continued with presentations from the hosts, showcasing four
                                    projects that effectively integrate historical tradition and digital innovation. The
                                    first was <a href="https://pkudh.org/project/sqj/">Shī Qiān Jiā</a>, an AI-powered
                                    platform capable of generating Chinese
                                    classical poetry. By entering just a few keywords, users can produce refined verses
                                    based on centuries of literary tradition. The second project introduced was
                                    the <a href="https://pkudh.org/project/rarebib/">National Rare Book Catalog
                                        System</a>, developed in collaboration with the National
                                    Library of China. It offers interactive interfaces, semantic visualizations, and
                                    mapping tools to explore the transmission and distribution of ancient texts.
                                </p>
                                <div class="image-container text-center my-4">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/roberta_2sm.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 600px;">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/roberta_3sm.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 600px;">
                                </div>

                                <p>The third project, <a href="https://pkudh.org/project/shidianguji/">Shídiǎn</a>, was
                                    presented as a robust platform for reading,
                                    annotating, and studying classical texts, featuring advanced tools such as character
                                    recognition, automated punctuation, and access to digitized materials. Finally, the
                                    session concluded with <a href="https://pkudh.org/project/gc/">Guanchao</a>, a
                                    project that brings Song-dynasty textual
                                    descriptions to life. Using generative AI, it transforms literary passages into
                                    animated scenes and visual representations inspired by traditional Chinese painting,
                                    offering a completely new way to "see" the past.
                                </p>
                                <p>The encounter fostered a valuable exchange on two levels — literature and Digital
                                    Humanities — opening up new perspectives for research and future collaboration.
                                </p>

