                                <h2 class="text-center mt-0">The LeggoManzoni workshop at Peking University</h2>
                                <p>
                                    <strong>March 20, 2025</strong>. On March 20, the University of Bologna team led an
                                    innovative workshop at Peking
                                    University, introducing Chinese students to digital humanities methodologies via
                                    Manzoni's I Promessi Sposi. The session featured two presentations: First, Prof.
                                    Paola Italia discussed the evolution of the novel from <i>Fermo e Lucia</i> to <i>I
                                        Promessi
                                        Sposi</i>. Next, Mariia Levchenko presented on multilingual digital editions and
                                    the
                                    LeggoManzoni platform's pipeline for integrating multiple translations across
                                    languages and time periods.
                                </p>
                                <div class="image-container text-center my-4">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/maria_1.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 400px;">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/maria_3.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 300px;">
                                </div>
                                <p>
                                    The highlight was the hands-on XML/TEI markup workshop, in which the Chinese
                                    students learned to encode Zhang Shihua's 1998 translation of the novel into
                                    Chinese. This peer-to-peer learning experience showcased the platform's
                                    segment-level alignment technology, enabling precise correlation between the
                                    original Italian text and the Chinese translation segments. Students practiced TEI
                                    encoding principles while contributing to the expansion of the TRADUCO MANZONI
                                    module. This module is part of a broader international collaboration between the
                                    universities of Bologna and Peking aimed at making Italian literature more
                                    accessible through innovative digital tools.
                                </p>
                                <div class="image-container text-center my-4">
                                    <img src="./assets/images/maria_2.jpg" alt="Visit to Pekino" class="img-fluid"
                                        style="max-width: 600px;">
